n policymaking and geopolitics. The illustrated diary includes picturesque descriptions of San Francisco, the Nome Gold Rush, Chukchi culture, Petropavlovsk, Vladivostok, and Nagasaki, Japan.Andrew A. Gentes's translation is based on an edition of Akifëv's book that was published in St. Petersburg in 1904. The diary shows how Russian and American views and cultural values clashed over a territory that is today more geopolitically important than ever. By documenting Akifëv's personal travels outside the expedition, To the Far North also demonstrates, in both human and personal terms, the role Russians played in shaping this region's history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aPhysiciansxTravel. 0aPhysicianszRussiavDiaries. 0aVoyages around the world. 4aHISTORY. 4aMemoir. 7aHISTORY / Russia / Soviet Era.2bisacsh  aWorld War I, Chukota Expedition, St. Petersburg, Russian goldmining, Arctic, Klondike and Nome gold rushes.1 aGentes, Andrew A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075184040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501774638?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501774638423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501774638/original  a978-3-11-075184-0  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles